            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s 16, standing in his father\u2019s garage in Hayward, the smell of oil thick in the air. His dad, wiping grease from a wrench, gestures with it toward the faint lights of San Francisco across the bay. \u201cThat\u2019s all smoke and mirrors, Davi. This,\u201d he says, tapping the engine block, \u201cthis is real.\u201d David feels a pang of guilt, knowing his heart is already over there, in the city of smoke. That moment created a lifelong drive to prove the intangible was real, a debt he feels he still owes.\n\n***\n\n2.\nIt\u2019s 1999, on the rooftop of the W Hotel during a launch party. The city is a carpet of diamonds below. A colleague, eyes wild with optimism, clinks his champagne flute against David\u2019s. \u201cWe\u2019re printing money! We\u2019re making the future!\u201d David believes it. He feels an intoxicating, god-like certainty that everything is possible. The memory is now a bittersweet reminder of a naive faith he can never get back, the high before the fall that taught him that belief, alone, is never enough.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe day the company folded in 2001, he walked through the silent office. The foosball table sat under a ghostly film of dust, and a whiteboard still held the hockey-stick growth projections from last quarter\u2019s all-hands. The silence was heavier than any sound he\u2019d ever heard. It wasn\u2019t just financial loss; it was the death of a shared religion. That quiet humility became the foundation of his new career, the calm, measured voice that could see past the hype to the structural flaws beneath.\n\n***\n\n4.\nHe remembers coming home near midnight to find his wife asleep on the couch, the TV on mute. He stood in the doorway for a full minute, watching her, knowing he should wake her but feeling like a stranger. The space between them felt vast and quiet. He went upstairs without a word. That silent, uncrossed threshold was the true end of his marriage, a quiet acknowledgment that the price for his professional ascent had been his presence in his own life.\n\n***\n\n5.\nLast year, at his daughter\u2019s student art show at UCLA, he watched her speak about an artist\u2019s use of negative space. He didn\u2019t grasp the theory, but he saw the unshakeable passion in her eyes\u2014the same fire he\u2019d once had for stock options and IPOs. He felt a surge of pure, uncomplicated pride. It was a world he couldn\u2019t enter but was honored to fund. That moment clarified his new ambition: to build something for himself that felt as real and passionate as her art."
